#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"In 2021, we want to focus on improving some of the very core features of "
"Tails, especially for **censorship circumvention**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To support our work in 2021, take a minute now to\n"
"<a href=\"https://tails.boum.org/donate/?r=pt\">donate and fight surveillance and censorship</a>!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title -
#, no-wrap
msgid "Censorship circumvention"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"We want to completely redesign how to **start Tor and configure Tor "
"bridges**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"This will make it easier for people in countries where accessing Tor is "
"blocked to circumvent censorship. According to data from the Tor project, "
"the top 5 countries by users of Tor bridges are Russia, Iran, the US, "
"Belarus, and China."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title -
#, no-wrap
msgid "Persistent Storage"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"We want to improve the interface of the **Persistent Storage settings**."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"Improving the Persistent Storage was your top priority when we surveyed our "
"users in July. We want to start by improving the usability of its core "
"features and rewriting this 9-year-old Perl application into Python GTK+. "
"This will make it possible to improve it faster in the future."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid "We also want to make it possible to persist Tor bridges."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title -
#, no-wrap
msgid "Security and maintenance"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To improve the security of all applications in Tails, we want to **migrate to\n"
"<em>Wayland</em>**. *Wayland* is a new display system for Linux that better\n"
"controls how each application interacts with the rest of the system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"For example, *Wayland* will fix how the [[*Unsafe Browser* can be used to "
"deanonymize you|doc/anonymous_internet/unsafe_browser#security]]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
msgid ""
"We will also release **Tails 5.0**, based on Debian 11 (Bullseye) at the end "
"of 2021. It will bring new versions of most of the software included in "
"Tails."
msgstr ""

